stories.text: I recently got into an argument with some friends (that are not programmers). They argued that nocode is a good thing to do projects on because they are very fast, and I could not think of an argument against that. So yeah, I feel kind of odd about the fact that noCode could someday replace a ton of programmers.

stories.text: I've created a Twitter clone on-chain to Ethereum's testnet (ropsten).  https://twitter-eth.vercel.app/ All tweets are automatically minted as NFTs. What I learned from building this is that it costs so much gas that it's useless. It costs $10 just to tweet, like, or RT. Deploying it costs over $100. Is this normal in Web 3.0?
stories.title: I've created a Twitter clone on-chain to Ethereum's testnet
